name: 3,3-Dimethylpentanedinitrile
Reason: The base structure of pentane has a melting point around -130 degrees Celsius. The two cyano groups (nitriles) introduced are electron-withdrawing and lead to stronger dipole-dipole interactions, which can significantly raise the melting point. Each nitrile might contribute approximately +70 to +80 degrees Celsius due to polarity and potential for linear molecular alignment enhancing crystalline packing. However, the presence of two bulky tertiary dimethyl groups provides steric hindrance and can disrupt efficient crystal packing, lowering the melting point. Dimethyl groups could each reduce the melting point by about -20 degrees Celsius. Hence, the predicted melting point would be the base pentane value plus the increases due to the nitriles minus the decreases due to the dimethyl groups.
Prediction: -130 (pentane baseline) + 70 (first nitrile) + 70 (second nitrile) - 20 (first dimethyl group) - 20 (second dimethyl group) = -30 degrees Celsius
